    interviewQuestions: [{q:"Explain closures and give a practical use case.",a:"A closure is a function that retains access to its lexical scope even after the outer function has returned. Practical uses include data privacy (module pattern), function factories, and maintaining state in callbacks.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is the event loop and how does it work?",a:"The event loop continuously checks the call stack. When empty, it picks the next task from the task queue (macrotasks) or microtask queue (promises, queueMicrotask). Microtasks always run before the next macrotask.",diff:"Hard"},{q:"Difference between == and ===?",a:"=== checks both value and type (strict equality). == performs type coercion before comparison (loose equality). Always prefer === to avoid unexpected behavior.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain prototypal inheritance.",a:"Objects can inherit from other objects via the prototype chain. When a property is accessed on an object, JS looks up the chain until it finds the property or reaches null. ES6 classes are syntactic sugar over this.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is the difference between var, let, and const?",a:"var is function-scoped and hoisted. let is block-scoped, not hoisted to initialization. const is block-scoped, must be initialized, and the binding cannot be reassigned (though objects/arrays it holds are still mutable).",diff:"Easy"},{q:"How does async/await differ from Promises?",a:"async/await is syntactic sugar over Promises. await pauses execution of the async function until the promise settles. It makes asynchronous code read like synchronous code and simplifies error handling with try/catch.",diff:"Medium"}],
