    interviewQuestions: [{q:"Explain React's reconciliation process.",a:"React's reconciler (Fiber) compares the new virtual DOM tree with the previous one. It uses a diffing algorithm that compares element types and keys to determine the minimal set of DOM mutations needed.",diff:"Hard"},{q:"What are React hooks and why were they introduced?",a:"Hooks let function components use state and lifecycle features. They were introduced to reuse stateful logic without classes, simplify component composition, and make related logic co-located.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain the useEffect cleanup function.",a:"The cleanup function returned by useEffect runs before the effect re-runs and when the component unmounts. It's used to cancel subscriptions, abort requests, or remove event listeners to prevent memory leaks.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is React.memo and when should you use it?",a:"React.memo is a higher-order component that memoizes the rendered output. It skips re-rendering if props haven't changed (shallow comparison). Use it for expensive components with stable props.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"Explain controlled vs uncontrolled components.",a:"Controlled components have their value driven by React state (via useState). Uncontrolled components manage their own state via the DOM (useRef). Controlled = React owns the data; uncontrolled = DOM owns the data.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"What are React Server Components?",a:"Server Components run only on the server and send rendered HTML to the client. They can access databases/files directly, reduce client bundle size, and stream content. They cannot use hooks or browser APIs.",diff:"Hard"}],
