    interviewQuestions: [{q:"What are Python decorators and how do they work?",a:"Decorators are functions that modify other functions or classes. They wrap a function using @syntax, allowing you to extend behavior without modifying the original code. They rely on first-class functions and closures.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"Explain the difference between a list and a tuple.",a:"Lists are mutable (can be modified after creation) and use square brackets. Tuples are immutable and use parentheses. Tuples are faster and can be used as dictionary keys; lists are better for dynamic collections.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"What is the GIL and why does it matter?",a:"The Global Interpreter Lock (GIL) is a mutex in CPython that allows only one thread to execute Python bytecode at a time. It limits true parallelism for CPU-bound tasks but is fine for I/O-bound work. Use multiprocessing for CPU-heavy tasks.",diff:"Hard"},{q:"How does Python's memory management work?",a:"Python uses reference counting as its primary mechanism, plus a cyclic garbage collector for reference cycles. Objects are allocated from a private heap. The gc module can be tuned for specific workloads.",diff:"Hard"},{q:"What are list comprehensions and generator expressions?",a:"List comprehensions create lists in a concise syntax: [x*2 for x in range(10)]. Generator expressions use parentheses and yield items lazily, saving memory for large sequences.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain context managers and the 'with' statement.",a:"Context managers define setup and teardown logic using __enter__ and __exit__ methods. The 'with' statement ensures resources are properly released. Created with contextlib.contextmanager decorator or class-based approach.",diff:"Medium"}],
