    interviewQuestions: [{q:"Explain the Node.js event loop phases.",a:"The event loop has phases: timers (setTimeout/setInterval), pending callbacks, idle/prepare, poll (new I/O), check (setImmediate), close callbacks. Each phase processes its callback queue before moving to the next.",diff:"Hard"},{q:"What is middleware in Express?",a:"Middleware functions have access to req, res, and next(). They can execute code, modify req/res, end the request cycle, or call next() to pass control. Used for auth, logging, parsing, error handling, etc.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"How do you handle unhandled promise rejections?",a:"Use process.on('unhandledRejection', handler) to catch unhandled rejections. In Node 15+, unhandled rejections terminate the process by default. Always catch promises or use async/await with try/catch.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"Explain streams in Node.js.",a:"Streams process data in chunks instead of loading everything into memory. Types: Readable, Writable, Duplex (both), Transform (modify data). Useful for large files, HTTP responses, and data processing pipelines.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is the difference between process.nextTick and setImmediate?",a:"process.nextTick runs immediately after the current operation, before the event loop continues. setImmediate runs in the check phase of the next event loop iteration. nextTick has higher priority.",diff:"Hard"},{q:"How does clustering work in Node.js?",a:"The cluster module forks child processes sharing the same port. Each process runs its own event loop. A master distributes incoming connections. It utilizes multi-core CPUs and provides fault isolation.",diff:"Medium"}],
