    interviewQuestions: [{q:"Explain the difference between an interface and an abstract class.",a:"Abstract classes can have constructors, instance variables, and non-abstract methods. Interfaces (since Java 8) can have default and static methods but no constructors or instance state. A class can implement multiple interfaces but extend only one class.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"What is the JVM garbage collection process?",a:"The JVM uses generational GC: Young Gen (Eden + Survivor spaces) for short-lived objects, Old Gen for long-lived ones. Algorithms include G1, ZGC, and Shenandoah. Minor GC collects young gen; Major/Full GC collects the entire heap.",diff:"Hard"},{q:"Explain the Java Collections Framework.",a:"JCF provides interfaces (List, Set, Map, Queue) and implementations (ArrayList, HashSet, HashMap, LinkedList). It includes algorithms (sort, search), iterators, and utility methods via Collections class.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What are Java Streams and how do they differ from I/O streams?",a:"Java Streams (java.util.stream) are for functional-style data processing on collections - map, filter, reduce, collect. I/O streams (java.io) are for reading/writing bytes or characters to files/network. Different concepts sharing the same name.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"Explain the SOLID principles.",a:"Single Responsibility: one reason to change. Open/Closed: open for extension, closed for modification. Liskov Substitution: subtypes must be substitutable. Interface Segregation: prefer specific interfaces. Dependency Inversion: depend on abstractions.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is the difference between HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap?",a:"HashMap is not thread-safe and can throw ConcurrentModificationException. ConcurrentHashMap uses segment locking for thread-safe operations without full synchronization. ConcurrentHashMap supports concurrent reads and writes.",diff:"Hard"}],
