    interviewQuestions: [{q:"What is the difference between S3 Standard and S3 Glacier?",a:"S3 Standard: immediate access, higher cost, for frequently accessed data. S3 Glacier: retrieval takes minutes to hours, very low cost, for archival data. Use lifecycle policies to transition between tiers.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain the shared responsibility model.",a:"AWS is responsible for security OF the cloud (hardware, software, networking). Customers are responsible for security IN the cloud (data, OS patching, firewall config, encryption). Scope varies by service type.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is the difference between IAM users and roles?",a:"Users have long-term credentials (passwords, access keys) for people or applications. Roles provide temporary credentials with specific permissions, assumed by trusted entities. Roles are preferred for cross-account and service access.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"How does Auto Scaling work?",a:"Auto Scaling automatically adjusts EC2 capacity based on demand. You define minimum, maximum, and desired capacity. Scaling policies trigger based on CloudWatch metrics (CPU, memory, custom metrics).",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is serverless computing on AWS?",a:"Serverless (Lambda, Fargate) runs code without managing servers. AWS handles provisioning, scaling, and patching. You pay per invocation/duration. Best for event-driven, variable workloads.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain VPC and its components.",a:"A VPC is a logically isolated network in AWS. Components: subnets (public/private), route tables, internet gateway, NAT gateway, security groups (stateful), NACLs (stateless), and VPC endpoints for private service access.",diff:"Hard"}],
