    interviewQuestions: [{q:"When would you use binary search?",a:"Binary search finds elements in O(log n) on sorted data. Use for: searching sorted arrays, finding boundaries, optimizing search spaces, finding peaks/valleys. Requires sorted input or monotonic property.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain dynamic programming.",a:"DP solves problems by breaking into overlapping subproblems. Memoization (top-down): cache recursive results. Tabulation (bottom-up): fill table iteratively. Identify: optimal substructure + overlapping subproblems.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is the time complexity of merge sort?",a:"Merge sort: O(n log n) in all cases (best, average, worst). It divides the array in half (log n levels) and merges at each level (n work). Stable sort but requires O(n) extra space.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain Dijkstra's algorithm.",a:"Dijkstra finds shortest paths from a source in weighted graphs with non-negative edges. Uses a priority queue. Greedily selects the closest unvisited node. O((V+E) log V) with binary heap.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"What is the difference between BFS and DFS?",a:"BFS: level-order, uses queue, finds shortest path in unweighted graphs, uses more memory. DFS: depth-first, uses stack/recursion, finds paths, cycle detection, uses less memory. Choose based on problem requirements.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain the master theorem.",a:"The master theorem solves recurrence relations of form T(n) = aT(n/b) + O(n^d). If d > log_b(a): O(n^d). If d = log_b(a): O(n^d log n). If d < log_b(a): O(n^log_b(a)). Applies to divide-and-conquer algorithms.",diff:"Hard"}],
