    interviewQuestions: [{q:"How do you approach a problem you've never seen before?",a:"1) Understand the problem fully (ask questions). 2) Break it into smaller parts. 3) Identify patterns with similar problems. 4) Start with a brute force solution. 5) Optimize step by step. 6) Test edge cases.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"Explain the 5 Whys technique.",a:"Ask 'Why?' five times to drill down to root cause. Example: Site crashed -> Why? High traffic -> Why? Viral post -> Why? No caching -> Why? No caching strategy -> Root cause: missing architecture review.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"How do you debug a production issue?",a:"1) Check logs and metrics. 2) Reproduce the issue locally. 3) Add strategic logging if needed. 4) Use binary search to isolate the change. 5) Check recent deployments. 6) Test hypotheses systematically.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"Describe a time you solved a complex problem.",a:"Use STAR method: Situation (context), Task (your responsibility), Action (steps you took), Result (outcome). Focus on your thinking process, trade-offs considered, and lessons learned.",diff:"Medium"},{q:"How do you prioritize when everything seems urgent?",a:"Evaluate impact vs effort. Use Eisenhower matrix: urgent+important first, schedule important+not urgent, delegate urgent+not important, eliminate neither. Communicate trade-offs to stakeholders.",diff:"Easy"},{q:"How do you handle disagreements about technical approaches?",a:"Listen to all perspectives. Focus on data and requirements, not opinions. Prototype if needed. Consider: scalability, maintainability, team familiarity, time constraints. Document decision and rationale.",diff:"Medium"}],
